	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Jentriken Aspenbark</b><br /><i>playing a shaman is easy. playing a GOOD shaman that makes people sit up and take notice is insanely hard.<br />
<br />
shaman or chanter or bard i'd hafta say. people notice when yer damn good.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>Mainly, what he said ^<br />
<br />
As for diffuculty, I'd rate bard at the top, due to the PITA known as twisting 4-5 songs, pulling, melee, and so forth. Not to mention the utter destruction of your wrists.<br />
<br />
But like Jentriken said, shamans are difficult to play if you are a GOOD/Excellent shaman. I never saw much excitement when I was in my 20's, but try upper 50's to 65.. and you'll find excitement. A good shaman *WILL* make or break that group.  Too many on a pull? Do that crowd control thing, slowem(dot the suckers too if they dont summon!), backup your cleric as needed - never know when he/she MIGHT go ld, keep dps/dots going avatar, haste... we are busy bees if we choose to be and your group will love you for it.<br />
<br />
Hell, my cleric went LD in kodtaz about 25% into a named mob(Hynid Howler) and I was the only healer left with an 8.8k tank.. kept that tank up for a decent amount of time til I finally could not keep up with the mob dps (hits for 1400ish, i heal for 1600-1800 with Tnargs, and up to 3500 on a crit, plus Trushar at 630/tick). Yes, the tank died, I died, and everyone but the bard, but i died cause of heal aggro and.. it goes downhill from there, and I died with it at 0%, bard finished it off heh.</p>
	
	
	
