<tr>
	<td class="alt1" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Kinedorf</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Initiate<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Mar 2004<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt1" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>In my opinion, the most specialized classes are the easiest to play. Clerics heal. Warriors hit autoattack and taunt. Wizzies wait until the mob is at x% health then nuke. I'm not saying that these classes cannot be challenging or enjoyable just that it is clearer how these classes can contribue well to a group. I've found that the less specialized a class is, the contribution to a group is more heavily influenced by player skill. The examples given above (e.g. bard, necro etc) are classes that have a wide breadth of abilitieslots of utility and they can influence the group immensely by the careful use of an ability. With regards bards, I have utmost respect for several people that I know who play bards but remember that being busy does not necessarily mean you are good at what you do. Anyone can sit there and mash keys. The question is, are they mashing the right ones at the right times?<br />
<br />
Rather than pick a class that is hard to play, I'd recommend picking one you think you will enjoy. Remember that, if a class is hard to play, chances are you will do a bad job initially and this may not be fun, particularly if the group suffers as a result of your mistake. Also take a look at your play style. If you like to solo often, for example, that removes a lot of classes from consideration. If you want to get a feel of different classes without investing the time to create a character and level it up, have a look at the other class sites and guides then have a scan of lucy to see what spells/disciplines they have. This should give you a bit of an idea. Do keep in mind that many classes don't get "class defining" abilities until well in to their progression and this may radically alter a classes play style at that level and beyond.<br />
<br />
Good luck!<br />
<br />
[Edit: spelling]</p>
	
	
	
