<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>SlimBritches</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Disciple<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: May 2004<br />
	Location: Inside 'dese SLIM BRITCHES! YOWZA!
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>Any shaman can hit malo then slow.  Then, when you get a couple extras in an easy PoP group, when they run around like fools screaming for heals instead of channeling root through turgur'd DPS and calmly backing aside... you know they aren't that great.  Had that happen with a 65 sham in group when I was leveling my warrior alt awhile back.  Was definitely annoying.<br />
<br />
There are a few things that indicate a good shaman, and the first and probably foremost is, as has been mentioned, they will always be casting a spell.  If they get to full mana, they should do something with it, and if not, they should be making more.<br />
<br />
A good shaman can run through a hectic situation on zero mana with canni/clickies/etc.  A bad shaman will shout oom and like, sit there and look pretty.<br />
<br />
Any class which deals with locking down mobs and controlling situations is a difficult class to play.  This lends more toward bards and enchanters, but can to a degree for shaman.  When things get hectic, you toss the slows, CC with VP/Root, toss a few Q's around and heal on top of those if needed.<br />
<br />
The problem is, in earlier content groups, that if, say, a cleric and an enc are in a group, you no longer are on main heals or crowd control, and also lose the ability to use rain.  At that point you're just a slower and third rate wizard wannabe.  Effective, but not exciting.<br />
<br />
I believe being good at any class is difficult.  It's just that some classes can be more forgiving when poorly played than others.  <br />
<br />
The thing is, it seems that some classes have a lot of tools with which to show skill.  As a shaman, if people go "wow, he's a darn good shammy,"  it's usually just because I stay calm and chain cast constantly during a situation that got out of control, slowing, maloing, rooting, HoT/Healing.  Those situations became rarer and rarer as I progressed further into content, where mobs would hit harder and were unrootable/unslowable.  I mean, when your duties are malo and slow, and nuke once and awhile, no matter how great you are, you'll hit a wall...<br />
<br />
You're canning and nuking constantly and still not breaking massive DPS, when a wizard with less skill can jabberjaw and then mash a key every once in awhile and ooh and aah the group more, as the beastlord pulls with awesome slows that are rarely resisted, splits off on one mob as his pet tanks the other, nukes, whatever.<br />
<br />
To answer your question, in my opinion, the hardest class to play effectively would be an enchanter, followed closely, if not tied with, bards, just because if you aren't a fast draw on mez, you can kill a lot of group members pretty fast.  Dealing with charm on high dps mobs also takes some skill as well.</p>
	
	
	
