<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Binter</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Disciple<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Jun 2003<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Purdypog</b><br /><i>Wow, I totally disagree that bard is the most difficult class to play to perfection.  It's a soloing charming enchanter without a doubt.  And I'm not talking the aa charm.<br />
<br />
Purdypog</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>I have a 65 chanter, so I can speak with experience here.  <img src="images/smilies/wink.gif" border="0" alt="" title="wink" smilieid="5" /><br />
<br />
Charm soloing is actually very easy.  Charm mob, guard, pull a victim, root it, do 1 point of damage, then back WAY away and let your pet kill it.  Lather, rinse, repeat.  Charm soloing is actually kinda boring, and is made even more so with Total Domination AA, which makes it harder for charmed pets to break charm.  A wise charm soloing enchanter never allows herself to get into a position where the pet can kill her, usually by ensuring a quick escape route if things go sour.  This isn't always possible, but veterans always try to set things up so they have as much an "out" as possible.<br />
<br />
Charming in GROUPS is where charming suddenly becomes very complicated.  A chanter charming in group has to worry about the pet as well as performing all the normal tasks a chanter performs.  He can't devote his attention on his pet completely, and that's bad.  Pets have this nasty habit of breaking charm the instant you start slowing the mob in camp.  They have this "radar sense" that lets them know when it's the absolute most inconvenient time to break charm, and they go for it with gusto.<br />
<br />
Charming enchanters like my alt Auli are paranoids.  We believe that everyone is out to get us, including our own groups...because they ARE.  <img src="images/smilies/wink.gif" border="0" alt="" title="wink" smilieid="5" /><br />
<br />
Seriously, being a paranoid is the only way you'll ever get good at charming in groups.  Grizzled veteran charmers buff the pet out the wazoo and arm it, and this is where you get the monstrous charm DPS.  Vallon's Quickening on a charmed pet with mage proc weapons equipped is just brutal.  You have to respect your pet, and also respect the idea that your group isn't respecting your pet.  They're gonna do stupid #%#&amp; like break mezzes or just stand there like dorks when charm breaks and you spam the "CHARM BROKEN" hotkey to warn them that you're now dealing with a runaway pet.  The worst of them actually complain:  "Why aren't you slowing the mob, you slacker?  Why aren't you mezzing?"<br />
<br />
"Because I'm trying to keep the pet from killing YOU by virtue of trying to keep it from killing ME, dorkwad!"<br />
<br />
But not everyone's like this.  Many people in high-end guilds have experience with charming enchanters, and when I play Auli I much prefer having these people in my groups, lol.  A single well-timed snare or stun pulls agro off me and lets me recapture the pet.<br />
<br />
Unfortunately, people who don't have much exposure to charming often don't let me do it.  Be it LDoN or grinding in PoP, more often than not I'm told no when I ask to charm.  I've even had people disband the group when I asked.<br />
<br />
You can't really blame them for being gun shy, though.  Charming in a group is one of those things that separates the good enchanters from the great enchanters...and there are WAY too many buff-bot-to-be Enchanters running around on Vazaelle, people way too high level for the skills they possess.<br />
<br />
Anyway...<br />
<br />
If you're looking for a challenging class to play, then I highly suggest sticking with your Shaman, or playing an Enchanter.  Shamans do a LOT with a LITTLE, pulling stunts that most other classes can't come close to duplicating because of the fact that we're "kinda good" at several different things, and our slow is very powerful.  Shamans are the toughest of all the casting classes, and bring to the table a varied array of spells that help them.  I have to agree with the others...there are shamans, then there are SHAMANS.  Those who are very good at playing the class find it the most challenging, because they push the envelope as it were, taking on things that others won't try, soloing in places few others dare to go.  The better a shaman you are, the more exciting and challenging the class becomes.<br />
<br />
But if shamans don't seem exciting enough, then try an Enchanter.  You get your first charm at level 12, and trust me, at level 12 charm is a spell that really pushes your adrenalin levels, because it's rather unreliable, lol.  Enchanters thrive in high-pressure situations, and a well played chanter can get groups through things that would kill them otherwise.<br />
<br />
But as it was pointed out, Enchanters can be boring if everything's going well.  It's only when you're in a group that pulls half the zone because there's an Enchanter in the group that makes them an utter blast to play.  Few things are as exciting as seeing 10 mobs come screaming into your camp and knowing that if your skills as an Enchanter aren't excellent, that train's gonna wipe your group.<br />
<br />
Those are the kinds of groups that Auli prefers, hehehe.  One of her favorite things to do is get the Lower Earth camp in BoT and kill off trains that comes boiling out of the other wings, except those rare ones that come out of Deep Earth and collect up just about every giant in the Earth wing...hehehe.  Not even she is that nuts.  If you don't have nerves of steel and aren't willing to take on trains, if the idea of pulling more than one mob at a time makes you wet your pants, then Auli doesn't like grouping with you.  <img src="images/smilies/biggrin.gif" border="0" alt="" title="big grin" smilieid="4" /><br />
<br />
Good shamans and enchanters are just that...good.  Well played Shamans and Enchanters are some of the most exciting classes in Everquest, because your skill is what pushes the envelope and makes it so exciting.</p>
	
	
	
		<div>__________________<br />Elder Binter, Vah Shir Prophet of Vazaelle.<br />
<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=856061">Magelo.</a><br />
Mistress Auli, Dark Elf Coercer of Vazaelle.</div>
	
	
