<tr>
	<td class="alt1" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Scalia</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Teacher<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Mar 2003<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt1" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>seventh.Tikoko</b><br /><i>id have to say thats wrong.. people only notice when you dont do your job right, when you do it properly no one will ever notice until their buffs fade.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>Oh, I don't know, that one time when the puller brought 5 in camp in LDON when we didn't have CC and all casters went oom half way through the fight, leaving me on heals, slows, root parking and off tanking, I think they noticed <img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="smile" smilieid="1" /><br />
<br />
Anyway, to go back to the original question, a lot of things in EQ are situational. If you are playing, say, a Cleric in a controlled environment, then yes, it can be as exciting as hitting the HoT button and the CH button once in a while. But if your group is trying to do something non-trivial, then you may find yourself juggling 5 different heals, root parking, stuns (if the mobs are stunnable), DA/DB (and when to click them off) and sometimes even off-tanking on low-damage unrootable mobs. Same deal with Wizards in non-trivial environemnts. They are easy to play as long as you know every mob's resists in every zone and can guess your MT's ability to hold agro 100% accurately - and if you are wrong, you get to tank a 1K hitter while wearing wet napkins for armor <img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="smile" smilieid="1" /><br />
<br />
Generally, I would advise against picking a class based solely on the perceived difficulty of playing it. There are other considerations that may prove to be more important in the long run. For example, if you don't like playing a support class, then don't -- it just won't be fun.</p>
	
	
	
	
